V. 7. First the advantages that all enjoy. The greatest is that no eivilian dares to strike you, nay more, if you strike him he holds his tongue and dares not show his grievance to the praetor. If he would have revenge he has his judge, a stout centurion in the camp, for soldiers may not go beyond for trial. Most just no doubt is the centurion’s judginent, and if I’ve right upon my side he'll give me satisfaction. But all the camp will see that my revenge shall prove a greater trouble than the wrong. And he’s a bold man who would dare offcnd so many boots and hobnails. And who would come so far to give his evidence? Let's dry our tears, nor trouble friends who will not fail to excuse themselves. The man who dares to witness to the assault is worthy of the olden times: a lying witness may be easier got against a townsman than a true against a soldier's fortunes and his honour.
